  "body": "A Hotter World Will Be Pricier\nPlus, can robots make coffee? ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ \n‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ \n‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ \n‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ \n‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ \n‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ \n‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌\nRead in browser \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/newsletters/2026-04-26/climate-change-could-make-inflation-worse>\n <https://www.bloomberg.com/weekend>\n\n \n<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click?s=1149019&li=17860118&m=cee68ef49e1e07dda471dbc72a2057c6&p=04262026080058&lctg=d27c9f4c-3a6e-4424-83d8-08bd5867b1d0&stpe=default>\n \n<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click?s=1149019&li=17860118&m=cee68ef49e1e07dda471dbc72a2057c6&p=04262026080058&lctg=d27c9f4c-3a6e-4424-83d8-08bd5867b1d0&stpe=default>\nWelcome back to The Forecast \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/account/newsletters/the-forecast> from Bloomberg \nWeekend <https://www.bloomberg.com/weekend>, where we help you think about the \nfuture — from next week to next decade.\n\nThis weekend:\n\n * US authorities are charging a gunman in a shooting at the White House \ncorrespondents’ dinner \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-26/alleged-shooter-at-white-house-press-event-in-custody?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n, during which President Donald Trump was rushed from the stage\n * Climate change is pushing up the cost of living \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-24/climate-change-is-already-making-the-affordability-crisis-worse?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n, and making central banks’ job harder\n * Keep an eye on: CEOs who use AI more heavily expect bigger workforce cuts\n * Scenarios: Are you prepared for ‘digital Darwinism’?\n * What are the chances… that a robot can prepare a cup of coffee in 10 years?\n * Plus, car touchscreens will come with breathalyzers built in\nA Hotter World Will Be Pricier\n\nIn the summer of 2022, a heatwave in Europe drove temperatures to a \nrecord-breaking 46C (115F) in Spain, scorching its olive-growing regions. In \nthe UK, chickens wilted in the heat, leading to a 9% drop in chicken-meat \nproduction from the year before. Northern Italy endured its worst drought in 70 \nyears, slashing harvests of risotto rice.\n\nResearchers calculated that climate change increased temperatures that summer \nin Europe by 1.25C on average — and by as much as 5.7C in some places. This was \na rare instance in which studies were able to estimate the direct effects of \nclimate change on prices, a phenomenon known as “climateflation” that’s only \nbeginning to be understood.\n\nOf course, droughts and storms have long affected prices. But as extreme \nweather becomes more common, price spikes once written off as temporary may be \nturning into something more lasting — a powerful new force that could further \ndisrupt household and national budgets already beset by an affordability \ncrisis. A cadre of economists, climate scientists and central bankers are \nstudying climate inflation’s effects, trying to piece together how it moves \nthrough the economy.\n\n“If you pick up a textbook and you look up the bit on inflation, inflation is \ntoo much money chasing too few goods. There’s no textbook that says, ‘the \nclimate’s cooking and we’re running out of stuff,’” says Mark Blyth, who runs \nBrown University’s Rhodes Center for International Economics and Finance.\n\nWhile climate shocks mainly push prices up in the short term, they can become \nlonger lasting if they change consumer inflation expectations — as research has \nsuggested they might.\n\n“The best way to avoid the damages from climate change is to have a global \ngreen transition,” says Marcus Mølbak Ingholt, senior lead climate economist at \nDanmarks Nationalbank, the Danish central bank. Absent that, a hotter world \nwill also likely be a pricier one.\n\n— Emma Court, Bloomberg Green\n\nFeature\n\nClimate Change Is Already Showing Up in the Cost of Living\n\nEconomists and central bankers are getting better at linking temperatures to \nprice increases.\nRead more \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-24/climate-change-is-already-making-the-affordability-crisis-worse>\n \n<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click?s=1103294&stpe=default&li=17860118&m=cee68ef49e1e07dda471dbc72a2057c6&p=04262026080058&lctg=d27c9f4c-3a6e-4424-83d8-08bd5867b1d0>\n\n \n<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click?s=1103294&stpe=default&li=17860118&m=cee68ef49e1e07dda471dbc72a2057c6&p=04262026080058&lctg=d27c9f4c-3a6e-4424-83d8-08bd5867b1d0>\nPredictions\n\nAsia’s Gen Z is facing a summer of discontent. “Already grappling with bleak \njob prospects and lackluster growth, it is now being stung by the shock from \nthe Iran war… The immediate impact is economic, but there is agrowing risk of \npolitical instability \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2026-04-23/get-ready-for-another-summer-of-rage-in-asia?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n.”— Karishma Vaswani, Bloomberg Opinion\n\nPortable brain scanners will help detect strokes in the middle of nowhere. \n“The device,resembling a compact astronaut’s helmet \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-24/portable-brain-scanners-aim-to-speed-stroke-diagnosis-in-remote-areas?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n, is designed to diagnose stroke in the field — telling clinicians whether it’s \na clot or a bleed so the right treatment can begin before brain cells start to \ndie.”— Jason Gale, Bloomberg Weekend\n\nCars will come equipped with touchscreens that double as breathalyzers. “Two \nGerman suppliers have come up with in-built sensors totest a driver’s blood \nalcohol level from a fingertip \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-23/too-tipsy-to-drive-german-suppliers-have-in-car-sensor-for-that?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n.”— Monica Raymunt, Bloomberg Technology\n\nBattery backlash will be the next flavor of Not-In-My-Backyard politics. “The \nUS is in the midst of a battery boom… But developers are increasingly \nencountering an implacable foe: communities afraid that large lithium-ion \nstorage farmscould spontaneously burst into flames \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2026-04-23/california-is-ground-zero-for-the-growing-battery-backlash?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n.”— Todd Woody, Bloomberg Green\n\nThe successor to the Large Hadron Collider — CERN’s proposed Future Circular \nCollider — will be a 57-mile loop running under Lake Geneva. It would dwarf the \nexisting Large Hadron Collider \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2026-04-24/particle-physics-needs-private-funding-for-cern-s-next-discovery?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n, in a bid to push the frontier of physics. It’s also expected to cost $19 \nbillion, and for the first time in CERN’s history a chunk of its funding will \ncome from private donors.— Paula Doenecke and Hugo Miller, Bloomberg Weekend\n\nAI companions will support seniors, whether we like it or not. It sounds \ndystopian, but much of the world “is aging fast andrunning short of caregivers \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2026-04-22/ai-is-coming-for-our-aging-parents-ready-or-not?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n. It’s no surprise that policymakers are turning to technology.” So far, \nthough, results are mixed.— Catherine Thorbecke, Bloomberg Opinion\n\nKeep an Eye On\n\nExecutives Who Use AI a Lot Expect More Job Losses\n\nWe’ve noted that the people who use AI more often are more excited about it \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/newsletters/2026-04-19/how-does-gen-z-feel-about-ai?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n andless worried that it will take their job \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/newsletters/2025-11-16/the-bbc-is-at-a-crossroads-after-trump-controversy?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n. On the other hand, they seem to be more likely to think that it’ll take your \njob.\n\nExecutives who spend more time using AI expect it to cause larger improvements \nin productivity and declines in employment at their firms compared to those \nusing it less frequently, according to a survey of 6,000 managers in the US, \nthe UK, Germany and Australia.\n\nThese relationships are still statistically significant when controlling for \nthe age and sector of the executives, according to the researchers, who broke \nout the data in response to questions from Bloomberg Weekend.\n\n“It’s pretty natural,” said Nicholas Bloom, an economist at Stanford and one \nof the study’s authors <https://www.nber.org/papers/w34836>. “Folks using AI \nare predicting large effects, and folks using AI are most likely to be \nprotected from it as [they] are riding the tech wave.”\n\n— Walter Frick, Bloomberg Weekend\n\nScenarios\n\nThe year is 2050. “Productivity is high, energy is cheap and plentiful, and \nthe economy is thriving,” write the authors ofa new scenario analysis from BCG \n<https://www.bcg.com/publications/2026/beyond-tomorrow-four-scenarios-for-the-world-of-2050>\n. Governments have come up with rules for the safe use of AI, and most people \nwork four days a week. Sounds nice.\n\nUnfortunately, that “AI abundance” scenario is just one of four outlined in \nthe BCG report. Two others focus more on geopolitics and climate change than \nAI, but the fourth they dub “digital Darwinism.” In that scenario, AI sparks \neconomic growth and even scientific progress — but it “accrue[s] to the tech \nelites in compute-rich nations — and to their investors. Everyone else lives \nmore precarious lives.” Gig work proliferates, as does workplace surveillance. \n“Persuasion-focused AI” disrupts political campaigns. “For relief, many escape \ninto AI-generated virtual worlds tailored to personal preferences and moods.” (\nMaybe the metaverse is still coming \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/newsletters/2025-11-23/2026-will-bring-more-ai-and-more-geopolitical-fragmentation?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n.)\n\nThe difference between these two possible futures is government, says Alan \nIny, one of the report’s authors and a partner at BCG. “Imagine a world where \nthe governments have less power and the corporations have more,” he says of the \ndigital Darwinism scenario. “If corporations do come up with some cool cancer \ntreatment there is no reason to assume, at least to me, that it will flow \nthrough to the masses.” In other words,when technical progress outpaces \npolitics, bad stuff tends to happen \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/newsletters/2024-12-29/2024-was-the-year-of-bots-bullets-and-bitcoin?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n.\n\nThe path to the abundance scenario isn’t seamless either. The report imagines \nmassive cyberattacks in the 2030s that lead to an AI treaty; it takes a \ndisaster to put the world on a better path. “If I just put the AI abundance \nscenario out there people would just say you’re crazy, you’re being naive, \nthat’s never going to happen,” says Iny.\n\n— Walter Frick, Bloomberg Weekend\n\nWhat Are the Chances...\n\nWill Robots Ever Be Able to Make Coffee?\n\nIn 2007, Apple co-founder Steve Wozniak predicted that robots would “never” be \nable to make a cup of coffee — meaning walk up to and operate an unfamiliar \ncoffee machine. But AI experts now predict that a robot will pass the “coffee \ntest” somewhere in the 2030s, with a median prediction of 2034.That’s from the \nLEAP forecasting competition \n<https://forecastingresearch.substack.com/p/when-will-robots-pass-the-coffee> \nrun by the Forecasting Research Institute, which we’vewritten about before \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2025-12-12/ai-forecasts-don-t-have-to-be-pure-guesswork?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n. The “coffee test” here “requires a robot to make a cup of coffee in three \ndifferent unstructured, unfamiliar environments of equivalent complexity to an \nordinary home, without making any mistakes.”\n\nIn addition to forecasts from AI experts, the LEAP project includes \npredictions from so-called “superforecasters” who’ve distinguished themselves \nwith accurate predictions in previous tournaments on unrelated topics. And \ntheir forecasts are slightly more bullish: The median superforecaster predicts \na robot will pass the coffee test in 2032.\n\nI guess put your coffee machine on notice? Starting next decade it’ll be robot \npour-overs only.\n\n— Walter Frick, Bloomberg Weekend \n\n(Disclosure: I was previously a contributing editor at FRI.)\n\nTell us what you think:\n\nWhen will a robot pass the “coffee test” — defined as the ability to prepare a \ncup of coffee in an unfamiliar home?\n\nThe median AI expert in the LEAP forecasting project predicts a robot will \npass the test by 2034. Too soon? Or too late?\n\n * Before or during 2034 \n<https://feedback.bloomberg.com/jfe/form/SV_0651ZDwxUhZIham>\n * After 2034 (if ever) \n<https://feedback.bloomberg.com/jfe/form/SV_0651ZDwxUhZIham>\nWeek Ahead\n\nMonday: China reports industrial profits, the UK’s King Charles III and Queen \nCamilla begin a four-day state visit to the US, the 12th Bloomberg CityLab \nsummit takes place in Madrid;Elon Musk’s lawsuit against OpenAI \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-24/why-did-elon-musk-and-sam-altman-fall-out-what-is-their-court-case-about?cmpid=BBD042626_SUNNL&utm_campaign=sundaynl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_term=260426&utm_content=3817>\n heads to court.\n\nTuesday: Rate decisions expected from Japan, Chile and Hungary; the Conference \nBoard reports US consumer confidence; Pershing Square is expected to price its \nIPO; Barclays, BP, Foxconn and GM report earnings.\n\nWednesday: Rate decisions from the US as well as Brazil, Canada and Thailand; \nthe Eurozone reports economic and consumer confidence; Meta, Alphabet, Amazon, \nMicrosoft, Samsung, Deutsche Bank and AstraZeneca report earnings.\n\nThursday: A number of countries release GDP (the US, Taiwan, Spain, Mexico, \nSaudi Arabia) and unemployment (Brazil, Colombia, the Eurozone, Germany, \nIsrael); the US and Eurozone will both release inflation data; China releases \nApril PMI; the ECB and BOE announce rate decisions; Apple and Eli Lilly release \nearnings.\n\nFriday: The UK and US release manufacturing PMI; Japan reports CPI; financial \nmarkets closed in several regions for May Day public holiday; Estée Lauder and \nExxon release earnings. \n\nWeekend Reads\n\nInterview\n\nHow to Negotiate with Iran\n\nWendy Sherman, the former US deputy secretary of state and architect of the \n2015 nuclear deal, says the current situation in Iran is harder, riskier and \nstrategically misjudged.\n <https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2026-wendy-sherman-weekend-interview/> \nEssay\n\nTrump Stumbled Into a Global Economic War. Xi Jinping Was Ready\n\nAs the US and Chinese leaders prepare to meet, the Iran conflict underscores \nBeijing’s resilience and the limits of Washington’s leverage.\n \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2026-04-24/iran-war-trump-to-meet-xi-as-balance-of-power-shifts-to-beijing>\nEssay\n\nThe Humbling of the Tories Shows the Limits of Party Politics\n\nThe Conservative Party has ruled Britain for most of the past century, \nregularly reinventing itself and sacrificing leaders. It may never get the \nchance again.\n \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-24/the-conservatives-decline-shows-the-limits-of-party-politics>\nEssay\n\nAsia’s Billionaires Are Bankrolling a Push for More Babies\n\nFrom Hong Kong to Seoul, tycoons are offering cash and perks to boost birth \nrates, testing whether private wealth can succeed where governments have \nstruggled.\n \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-24/asia-s-billionaires-offer-cash-incentives-to-boost-birth-rates>\nDispatch\n\nPokémon’s Multibillion-Dollar Card Boom Sparks a Crime Wave\n\nAs a childhood hobby becomes an asset class, theft and fraud are spreading \nacross the fast-growing market.\n \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-24/pokemon-card-boom-sparks-a-crime-wave-as-values-soar>\nHave a great Sunday and a productive week.\n\n— Walter Frick, Jackie Bischof and Katherine Bell, Bloomberg Weekend; Emma \nCourt, Bloomberg Green\n\nMore from Bloomberg\n\nEnjoying The Forecast? Check out these newsletters:\n\n * Breaking News Alerts \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/account/newsletters/breaking-news-alerts?utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_campaign=sundaynl>\n for the biggest stories from around the world.\n * Markets Daily \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/account/newsletters/markets-daily?utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_campaign=sundaynl>\n for what’s moving in stocks, bonds, FX and commodities.\n * Morning Briefing Americas \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/account/newsletters/morning-americas?utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_campaign=sundaynl>\n for catching up on everything you need to know.\n * Wall Street Week \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/account/newsletters/wall-street-week?utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_campaign=sundaynl>\n for David Westin’s weekly newsletter where the top newsmakers in finance talk \nstories of capitalism.\nExplore all newsletters at Bloomberg.com \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/newsletters?utm_medium=email&utm_source=newsletter&utm_campaign=sundaynl>\n.\n\nWe’re improving your newsletter experience and we’d love your feedback. If \nsomething looks off, help us fine-tune your experience by reporting ithere \n<https://bmedia.iad1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_dhba7RmVMUuC9WC?bconnectId=E303D6C8D22F4D76B970EDBCD765D6CB>\n.\n\nFollow Us\n\n <https://www.instagram.com/bloombergbusiness/> <https://x.com/business> \n<https://www.linkedin.com/company/bloomberg-news/posts/> \n<https://bsky.app/profile/bloomberg.com> \n<https://whatsapp.com/channel/0029Va2h58LDeONAZNBpcg09>\nYou received this message because you are subscribed to Bloomberg’s The \nForecast newsletter. If a friend forwarded you this message,sign up here \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/account/newsletters/the-forecast?source=NLshare> to \nget it in your inbox.\n\nUnsubscribe \n<https://www.bloomberg.com/account/newsletters/the-forecast?source=newsletter_unsub&email=wschenk@gmail.com&hash=c25db30fe230dc8471e12ce12e692b4b7198b0f0>\nBloomberg.com <https://www.bloomberg.com>\nContact Us <https://www.bloomberg.com/help/?s=newsletters>Bloomberg L.P.\n731 Lexington Avenue\nNew York, NY 10022\n\n <https://www.liveintent.com/powered-by>| \n<https://www.liveintent.com/ad-choices> \n<https://links.message.bloomberg.com/s/eh/qMvkhbDZqJAYNBHvzAzYG144CSmvesgGatAm_tzGcqT6sua7Z--OKiAUbp5fIo0Q9nA1-7_x84srqHK2Od6Vqr8Bz5zSFCkAGVmZQMbsOcIa0z4goD9cgS5bFpwV