erit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">Bloomberg Weekend</a>, where we help you think about the future — from next week to next decade.</p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">This weekend:</p><ul style=\"margin-top:24px;padding-inline-start:24px\"><li style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:400;line-height:1.4;font-size:16px\"><a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/YA06XG7Hx4oFN8ZVh37VbR8OqNVdFSFUClXvba07jOQG50JfrimhTyr7kItQdmiLfnGajsMx4m1dsKX-aftwLElovzZ6mm5r85vIVdhjY9yGazxJeaEs7QhRdEC62xi2179dUUxfZRNLHQmc4Yo57V6Td872y2IwcIowHDxcBkTsTDUtfLB3GqxFIX3TZLZTmtPB2nbQmlzmojw29r1-wd7eUF-0wzyLNud3LlJsliPdmykSP2ES6jAHLWoxDFZw8Mr4qmIODScgcuwVpljTqGkc8Jo8y0lf-jqLTkM8w6qzfGS4Bhe1fs8MS8j0avZPAlO2S7xHop9-jRhDfQpCTe1HrdtVzjeCmZcg805UyJRDirdLa5Ei7DDIO4lRXc0laSZR0MncFdcv3f5vCE4-T_otLoB0RKZhFMjmuQzlkNG9VjERMLueCgEnIA2WtdYmZphgsbqDMQyrQbpWiwChFtxxGt8DFKuQe7DQ017u0nBoQDxWUkYTA10DUx1xhVRI7MQ48C7wU1d06DwzmQBPa6YsJ55ceA0nZQ/IbMt0dch9SBt0tFkKy-7Juv-0MOKRe_r/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"Gunman Detained, Trump Evacuated After Shooting at Press Dinner\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid;font-size:16px\">US authorities are charging a gunman in a shooting at the White House correspondents’ dinner</a>, during which President Donald Trump was rushed from the stage</li><li style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:400;line-height:1.4;font-size:16px\"><a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/FnmR-CaYPGpmRL_jNR3vRxOHBUPnuyp4UNGOmqt5Rvpxmdhbvq8E9PZQEptksm0q3bL5WgPnqJcKTnhzXwKvfCzKLu2UWv8WKVja618D5GFoK_8UtGcsgMPsr1iKqOwmLh0QueZECD5dzLuUYWKcOXNREqGhsTFveOgoc70zZB-DxL5f4RXo_8K2cL_BRMFseMGeivJxnYH0VTSu7WFPmPW2M1bvwr3AMUBQzRrBzfrZFaga2Y2jq54A__imkjHymNXwE0xyc4M18QblgYrpl2YhHzGYTYLC-DSQOIJY8cITImyR1vxcVv71227-mU2uhlcWQQtDVUv7dEmMZXgpUYewi7PqQ0mN55rNsKPmY4P8FxURaLLAw7vfz-jvbkohoc-UeByxJF2jB27HG97H_KFaSbYqyd5kAYMIJz2VnmFDmI9Y-k08WX2gPpnM0qo_uxCSV2No-GHnnYO7VEpYShMTwgXpjISMy0kQUBvk7O-QFQb56dBpmBLoxc-o0F0ChV9F8Z8LiOAiDDn0S8jihZfzs1pUZZi7d2v4y-pNUIEYpqY/w_w2RuPqhE_0ClBw2m_WRH6yhsofmunn/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"Climate Change Is Already Showing Up in the Cost of Living\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid;font-size:16px\">Climate change is pushing up the cost of living</a>, and making central banks’ job harder</li><li style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:400;line-height:1.4;font-size:16px\">Keep an eye on: CEOs who use AI more heavily expect bigger workforce cuts</li><li style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:400;line-height:1.4;font-size:16px\">Scenarios: Are you prepared for ‘digital Darwinism’?</li><li style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:400;line-height:1.4;font-size:16px\">What are the chances… that a robot can prepare a cup of coffee in 10 years?</li><li style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:400;line-height:1.4;font-size:16px\">Plus, car touchscreens will come with breathalyzers built in</li></ul><h2 style=\"font-size:24px;line-height:30px;font-weight:700;padding-top:12px;border-top:1px solid;margin-top:40px\">A Hotter World Will Be Pricier</h2><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">In the summer of 2022, a heatwave in Europe drove temperatures to a record-breaking 46C (115F) in Spain, scorching its olive-growing regions. In the UK, chickens wilted in the heat, leading to a 9% drop in chicken-meat production from the year before. Northern Italy endured its worst drought in 70 years, slashing harvests of risotto rice.</p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">Researchers calculated that climate change increased temperatures that summer in Europe by 1.25C on average — and by as much as 5.7C in some places. This was a rare instance in which studies were able to estimate the direct effects of climate change on prices, a phenomenon known as “climateflation” that’s only beginning to be understood. </p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">Of course, droughts and storms have long affected prices. But as extreme weather becomes more common, price spikes once written off as temporary may be turning into something more lasting — a powerful new force that could further disrupt household and national budgets already beset by an affordability crisis. A cadre of economists, climate scientists and central bankers are studying climate inflation’s effects, trying to piece together how it moves through the economy. </p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">“If you pick up a textbook and you look up the bit on inflation, inflation is too much money chasing too few goods. There’s no textbook that says, ‘the climate’s cooking and we’re running out of stuff,’” says Mark Blyth, who runs Brown University’s Rhodes Center for International Economics and Finance. </p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">While climate shocks mainly push prices up in the short term, they can become longer lasting if they change consumer inflation expectations — as research has suggested they might. </p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">“The best way to avoid the damages from climate change is to have a global green transition,” says Marcus Mølbak Ingholt, senior lead climate economist at Danmarks Nationalbank, the Danish central bank. Absent that, a hotter world will also likely be a pricier one.</p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><em style=\"font-size:16px\">— Emma Court, Bloomberg Green</em></p><div style=\"max-width:580px;margin-top:24px\"><a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/tRCNomJysRY_JpiP6rId0HrgJME-tZ9z4Djla876MooutNdj83nmOq3t-MpcJqTnBx87uiy9AQNx5FQDPXzLiC7m0LMZKc-DvLLDVlv4nVPrjXtzgJ9YwGJqSy0FRpEUGLoPOfyH8k4xKNAMECpqAwLig654akR_wFTMkIbTkxrs1wmEiUCYNNaXXXwa3jXxvX9LXIoWAT-7Tc6ieGt2MjHPsnt0fCCUg5ONBmzUu6f87SQ6E39yVGNkfrFh3VbwXCy9cVfBsh5X20q8oU3c3fFbGbufdeRjmtl_oexzn7AteEkzAoHWwwN78dh95LXwJwTu4UdbP-6oLekxK_-gvV6Ik3WMSzTDDi9NV5l98MuyUSLcmmtjlhxcnuTnx5PiBtU0RrGljHwxEGZ-funm/GpcecE-HEIVkVpeZ-KHFVGMr7NsIOp1w/20\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid;font-size:inherit;color:inherit;text-decoration:none\"><div><!--[if mso]><table width=\"580\"><tr><td><img src=\"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/iJpzSL2eHYeU/v0/-1x-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"580\"/></td></tr></table><div style=\"display:none\"><![endif]--> <img src=\"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/iJpzSL2eHYeU/v0/-1x-1.png\" alt style=\"width:100%;max-width:580px;display:block\"><!--[if mso]></div><![endif]--></div><p style=\"line-height:normal;margin:12px 0 0 0;color:inherit;text-decoration:none;font-size:14px !important\">Feature</p><h2 style=\"line-height:normal;font-weight:700;margin:12px 0 0 0;font-size:20px !important\">Climate Change Is Already Showing Up in the Cost of Living</h2><p style=\"line-height:1.4;margin:12px 0 0 0;color:inherit;text-decoration:none;font-size:16px !important\">Economists and central bankers are getting better at linking temperatures to price increases.</p><div style=\"display:block;width:100%;height:40px;text-align:center;line-height:40px;border:1px solid;border-radius:8px;box-sizing:border-box;margin:16px 0 0 0;font-size:14px !important\">Read more</div></a></div><table width=\"auto\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\" style=\"margin-top:20px\"><tr><td align=\"center\" valign=\"top\" style=\"padding:0\"><a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/s/c/2qyqZee9d_iOO5pyD1wTLdBlSLOJQvrvp8FOHepzkZQkkSraz8-Hr5E6EPi6pj1xCZLO-Q6oOmx9_WSWgBT7XjLq_rkrPIbCZ-2EUsRHsL0Twt53YC_-fNm0CVfFjjD9hgpWJ4lVJngx_ztt1qNXyUXFV9lf760uu3nxo5jq3eDsMOAbYF1vOlwc9AgFOFb5DdWOWO3X3xlrrIPsv9yDE7uWJEiuCZdqtDUsjDFSpRW4aWy1QH-DDRFpMyMcdldKlPT-fToOdRolUbDePyv6-GEqiuY1Bw4VuaVn-b4rv4PUQKYdp2Qf1Y-VoqdTZWuyIlKacEOQUcnflVDAfa0SzWo-VAKV_QLKyGzIAILU5uJBxeoQZMuN218FehGzE0nb5KNv4nzZDw2gO0lE9TfOOezeJEQUzGo4d3dIyri9Lpvkk5AMtmaEyY_8MUN7-tqqkG5vF_D2TYuLUkAAwg/JOE3CNO1AigePM4Zi981JjK6sLOC8wQc/20\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size