er noreferrer\" title=\"Portable Brain Scanners Bring Stroke Diagnosis to the Middle of Nowhere\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">resembling a compact astronaut’s helmet</a>, is designed to diagnose stroke in the field — telling clinicians whether it’s a clot or a bleed so the right treatment can begin before brain cells start to die.” <em style=\"font-size:16px\">— Jason Gale, Bloomberg Weekend</em></p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><strong style=\"font-size:16px\">Cars will come equipped with touchscreens that double as breathalyzers. </strong>“Two German suppliers have come up with in-built sensors to <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/HojNqxep777Jvcv-PJkNOMScEorCHs2-XsQQUXViTtmIPlvl1NH4sDqWPtpgMkDWmNBdxzAak1gWjIziI4vPBMWBNwfQoIqcnZC6D9m0r_7yyMEr9EHnY49zoemynank-vvD74x9GGsj8IyuR33f03-qH6OddJ9PALdSxeC-5kyE5E9Q2DlLlA-1lXKEdHqWrKthnqtxtaHoIFmnUgIcOzm1rbcPThuimAR7f4v38rTXkBBMe3VVmhaxLF2gPO54ilCL6wUI03Km1LVgUEBbhVxndIHBS2vDWt7PS_fVBRCxLjU5ZDgoItWdXJBSNXjExxKRM1A2rZp6LYOjvgISUgjgE-rIt7fZjLkdkcZCtT248bQTFoiUKWYyyH4Kd32CW_g5qzVDC4KN4fODGN9g3dS-WJJo7d6Ir69InSnKrkORgvolcM_dNRQAqpSgQjLIPz3RPLIWhFJ5DQt73KbcbdwXVEXBGCXwx8XXkxIC-Y8FKZZuefG9tPRMZYMKsy-knd_vL1OnklNpp9ogqe_SFe0D2Ke96gQTRGGTo6-LeAlK4B4/2qI9QhVty7WFQc_w9c63kJMAy3R8QGTj/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"Too Tipsy to Drive? German Suppliers Have In-Car Sensor for That\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">test a driver’s blood alcohol level from a fingertip</a>.” <em style=\"font-size:16px\">— Monica Raymunt, Bloomberg Technology</em></p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><strong style=\"font-size:16px\">Battery backlash will be the next flavor of </strong><strong style=\"font-size:16px\"><em style=\"font-size:16px\">Not-In-My-Backyard </em></strong><strong style=\"font-size:16px\">politics.</strong> “The US is in the midst of a battery boom… But developers are increasingly encountering an implacable foe: communities afraid that large lithium-ion storage farms <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/XuNqxlMGTZwNzU4d7i1aSSM_dbLaiJYoZVRVBTa85zC9QJUl3pSTzH2GBxacil5lGQL6YFkIqXpz1ee3g1C5KBXAlPNxZ4nf27dQ1Q_KJFA7PvoqdtEsHDmcyhU0ouqiK_HQYztc_JO2eeadcrTxs3nw5qWSU3hJ5by6AbKJiO5Crb1aMKNq0h8IPGzXPtMZFH6XWgitQWXzfgYetryWvUXpXGoyQxnZ4XvahQEp9EINcTIT1gT4CXDurg5D6TgXMWJNHuFdpUDLfFmA9oZ8fLSNrphUL-X8ray1zvVSIjKkanbqCTP1PN_tdMm56GBPi1mMS3Q2_Vu2yfpMEoUsDzl1sfzGtA5Wr33o4WZQI6dnBJ-AArYQcd_tepBOV34-ccVXkEgXxq3sG2MXXI0xzwwkixUfskHjzOxVpRqhSeEoulED3t0R3h8LKqp72RRHtzaKDVSBUkYW2vAwMFrp6rFtafr7rEBhiWpy2D7jljMLniMZtzZ6j80qCz0bIIUrsQZu3aIAmDVhNv_uykLpcvjIPzWbXrNOlG7cUFcp/SovYK8u_eOQZ2-2_rXMz8-Dq3u5pflhs/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"California Is Ground Zero for the Growing Battery Backlash\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">could spontaneously burst into flames</a>.” <em style=\"font-size:16px\">— Todd Woody, Bloomberg Green</em></p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><strong style=\"font-size:16px\">The successor to the Large Hadron Collider — CERN’s proposed Future Circular Collider — will be a 57-mile loop running under Lake Geneva.</strong> <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/fsXOSiPHQ9Son-kwuGGWOjUe8YnvYuNjxcZniGtlqqDAaz9lmXwbXxBTK3w8o_4iiiWjVZoxyd1sUIof1VeFki32wAt02cF5mcZKeGCE7knATMcodkPlsNOxIMbLOg8xpFfs1XtzMLqckmxYKHGAlRPXeavl-EcioY6i50Zlhbjj5uNzzvwVgr3rKOfzlMKCk_eCJJq1D2j_VPP3lCb5savhIH9dzG4ie899ZEyL7U5m_CQLbX3SqNGzbxA_V3K2NbXODuDObJH9D_F1XRGhPGnHC6HNObrZHhAa9nC1ighJfUhyM500_Mc6zkerrqwnAxBOS5YGfca0rWqwu_vRHZN7wzCp06ne243irAYFHiaQ-knEmt6W77sqBYN-pw821J_IaOz6Wfv-D98Q74iU9bSrwvtTWmauKQv1x02SpRbkKyA5gKvu4oeEHsNyElYD-taNUDaBk0H9MJfh8jkQtZS8F6q0EXGex8prpNyZuIO7CKn-G1Y4p6TJC-YfEtu9lUH2DngysAtD21VPI7E9IzjDy9BqoS2JfpLuOlf_Ei3yb6Dt/8cwLGicSfkxl1NnrLWhg43pIJ3foyQaw/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"Unlocking the Deep Mysteries of the Universe Will Require Private Money\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">It would dwarf the existing Large Hadron Collider</a>, in a bid to push the frontier of physics. It’s also expected to cost $19 billion, and for the first time in CERN’s history a chunk of its funding will come from private donors. <em style=\"font-size:16px\">— Paula Doenecke and Hugo Miller, Bloomberg Weekend</em></p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><strong style=\"font-size:16px\">AI companions will support seniors, whether we like it or not. </strong>It sounds dystopian, but much of the world “is aging fast and <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/Il0SNbjwy21TMS6E5BitiLMBR4hHUqoYwAUANME2ZAK-lknS-koNhRfeAhSJUjyqg5Q-m2RMybzPHBpjLZ73aS1fyAlAPP_e33KdyRK0xBL5TMuCng8aASvK4yAwf4L9izerxSWLjm4Z8RCIa47O5HvzrulV8lnNo8LCgUQhdQLwLSJ10tRatqIPeK7jiRUZ5Nqv0a4qAVo4v0Kqf-3HixkiIIub7fQZ5kvYA4fnyr8gLn4LfegGsDgo1X11JWJD2hmnsgDuJX25aEnCGrA66dSPq235arUjg8wNy5UelcHMPQ3x20laS07u4rTyuEpiHAw_D_o9htFFNKiekoPlH6W_zkbeV_10ZY45Rz5ENsaSrs6uCTDJl5pqikjLZmgXAOwtvs6xTDFpFGA34M_BG2Nt_RBXxb8y5EluMUZ31kIUND_P4ymVxm9my9fOSoDnrrhR53Xk7NFtk-WIFdHXYHBtOU9S6Kik5euMrZLpvdfSkFMNcUVDe90CzZv00ehLcKYFm6soYYyr1IrPxXApAKxmF5Pb7w/C113YH3ihZ3-xlEGo06whSj5A7mo-i9P/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"AI Is Coming for Our Aging Parents, Ready or Not\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">running short of caregivers</a>. It’s no surprise that policymakers are turning to technology.” So far, though, results are mixed. <em style=\"font-size:16px\">— Catherine Thorbecke, Bloomberg Opinion</em></p><h2 style=\"font-size:24px;line-height:30px;font-weight:700;padding-top:12px;border-top:1px solid;margin-top:40px\">Keep an Eye On</h2><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><strong style=\"font-size:16px\">Executives Who Use AI a Lot Expect More Job Losses</strong></p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">We’ve noted that the people who use AI more often are <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/PiS8VepGiExSESNdk_fsMIuYSc5UJWOW_urYgZ3hY5UkeqJoNK213zSQRHYcvx7AmPhl1XmjDeFcQRjmg92E4GDAnnzmiNH7gS7Z9naElkfjNJoR88-vubMP_k4ncvQqOqh309vhWSTuso5vCpSgQdwWMTZbGTLQSrhkFdJJRttiCLyn5-XvvmEPPreG7ra0XkQwy64cbw-CWMEbJYDqteBQP8pxjAfx9IoGPFQBGRvN6OyBF4e-zUNYdbv_OAQgpFeTsEH0Fiiqo5qn2phyM007kFGoUaE9W7AZzY1xFnbBHRER2GjFlYGJXEGQPksnqLoCar3Ivcgl10zn7JFftff6Erc2jK1dOvOaMP-bWpm1wreqLyLuyPBpjArDSgP5w6FBgGd1Du4yDKpgf0xe2arzJj79mELbwQPF4AJkzwUbAJmtC7lhMhcdJ3ilQ8ah3oE_vFQG7OSzxWSUR2H04KYIsYOQlUnUPw8Vvldz8GNDfvU851KG6gsVIp2fkk6td2iT/B6f2eV0JYdxHMOpnV5JxokbrUvNQAPH6/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"Gen Z Is Souring on AI\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">more excited about it</a> and <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/godA_wVpJ9du15cfPnMx_mF3Ci_y-1XxXhw7oFEi5eBeP47m2QyhiN92Pq7ScV42m4KEeibsOypnMdArsiG3clYUrHJ-R8fofla1k8wY2CrsFAHXS0lHiQyI9lV5cKkRBUWZ96vzq5sV4bJGCbIHCs0UL2saVhQmkEFTfpKkS_P7izkg1JDsPYHBbDI6hALR3cOhd7kYC2fAtIz_rlsBLyNFi1RxsVH3o2SWXtp5YKg3RzBfsGHGTia8WrQ_SmfSrDEfjzftroN87x8MihaXFZhIBO1JpRQc1YBGPd25INVVsJcBBc5hqVyNmdH7rvlLMfrA1aDohmmPomvTQoYdbfpNBhZOmgBC2YiRedeT4LyrPo0ecJUxVeY8W_ZK8lNi7bf-8osBg8kOc9rqwpLyewnZ17j05kdtYuDa3ri2cSc0AyCfQvV7R5Srzne8raaflITqfL4uz2b5SMknrfzSIRGm_EHNxR2LzhL6MV-EJ1km5KemltDo0vzMKu7FSSdZPLR0KDssftHbfauzark0uMx6Ub74vUGKDA/SLnwu05fxQyFS6xfi-qJwFwG922wvVqq/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"The BBC Is at a Crossroads\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">less worried that it will take their job</a>. On the other hand, they seem to be more likely<em style=\"font-size:16px\"> </em>to think that it’ll take <em style=\"font-size:16px\">your </em>job.</p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">Executives who spend more time using AI expect it to cause larger improvements in productivity and declines in employment at their firms compared to those using it less frequently, according to a survey of 6,000 managers in the US, the UK, Germany and Australia.</p><figure style=\"margin:20px 0;max-width:580px\"><!--[if mso]><table width=\"580\"><tr><td><img src=\"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/iN8ZAovVAwEo/v3/pidjEfPlU1QWZop3vfGKsrX.ke8XuWirGYh1PKgEw44kE/-1x-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"580\"/></td></tr></table><div style=\"display:none\"><![endif]--> <img src=\"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/iN8ZAovVAwEo/v3/pidjEfPlU1QWZop3vfGKsrX.ke8XuWirGYh1PKgEw44kE/-1x-1.png\" alt style=\"width:100%;display:block;margin-bottom:4px;max-width:580px\"><!--[if mso]></div><![endif]--></figure><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">These relationships are still statistically significant when controlling for the age and sector of the executives, according to the researchers, who broke out the data in response to questions from Bloomberg Weekend.</p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">“It’s pretty natural,” said Nicholas Bloom, an economist at Stanford and <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/s/c/uvmRbM1gQss9ikvchoQxPb11EUJlFHXOw6xwnIeMfvMgpesaFQtzUjUl-si7tWUadR-f-kWvYToBdMnXs-Z9nxmMzXUo3zva_zoDYHJoSNKr5VUOqihgn0sySNQ7vLsmn8ZliNSkUhZHyxXoTCtRzf_-kXiDoHoxvRNokHMmjO_88V4gr7nqyis1OXXNA_7qfOeHHQYI_w1RN9j-SLaeP-BC8aSfA7wjfmUj3NlJVQyh9lzDad2lP5VWLN-4YEYKT87-uctQa-u3yEfSvtxtLtzdeb8rMQ5rhsEw6kqiiw/ZGCVAaLoZamZ8ycqP79JH3-QMfY5dzyA/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"Firm Data on AI\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">one of the study’s authors</a>. “Folks using AI are predicting large effects, and folks using AI are most likely to be protected from it as [they] are riding the tech wave.” </p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><em style=\"font-size:16px\">— Walter Frick, Bloomberg Weekend</em></p><h2 style=\"font-size:24px;line-height:30px;font-weight:700;padding-top:12px;border-top:1px solid;margin-top:40px\">Scenarios</h2><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">The year is 2050. “Productivity is high, energy is cheap and plentiful, and the economy is thriving,” write the authors of <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/s/c/A4Df_lKCwbZLOuuVNxchG57YiqpAA0o13SYFKjpn-rOpBC1MmY9awpSOjLCXsbZyWJozENXphh5NOsSU2N-OWQula-KftQM7VdE73YZN4OEYyMuFsxP8ybUq4rxpstK-viMO0JFQP6VwhWWIOh0gEeujyUVKx6a08lK0ocG-2AX_sJWc2aPa2XdGiJpWXiXq6_FTI2EcQlt_GpQhjBFBQE68HrFbHTdZOhQQ8SR_B8anJDi9LmiqF_rc-wnFNeevqWUbPn2K4iHM-kT-xXM5JagE5DCECZCqFz62b_3pPVwnrkG_g3ODxxNMhQb2DJRo1tQiMkfb6yZLy0PCWUF957sRimrc-ClyOe9HBXxFTzOwmEUK84vM/_j_zZYEKBYyTFRS31pl1R75RuPD0VAEs/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"Beyond Tomorrow: Four Scenarios for the World of 2050\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">a new scenario analysis from BCG</a>. Governments have come up with rules for the safe use of AI, and most people work four days a week. Sounds nice. </p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">Unfortunately, that “AI abundance” scenario is just one of four outlined in the BCG report. Two others focus more on geopolitics and climate change than AI, but the fourth they dub “digital Darwinism.” In that scenario, AI sparks economic growth and even scientific progress — but it “accrue[s] to the tech elites in compute-rich nations — and to their investors. Everyone else lives more precarious lives.” Gig work proliferates, as does workplace surveillance. “Persuasion-focused AI” disrupts political campaigns. “For relief, many escape into AI-generated virtual worlds tailored to personal preferences and moods.” (<a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/WF8RwvWPRiCsfKDawyfIQrYxnp6wFOW4UsrXs19ICFopZ48UgKXQwd8iCnpedCwB4syAMkus9rX5Ayx1pTIsiOV3PQARrJEIV-UxqNeoGXRuRoE9Tg9NjkJGoxJfyU-cd1BTSL2DyTHZyWWHq0bmNofKSZJ0uAFSlP1cJ5guBDQVF_Gm2tLt71ND97XHU1PnSXCxQNIPrl2-jHmRi_IQpA4Fc5yFtS9V51HuG4SXdjMgMWho_kjvGBrLoXL8UJocitSBurszxx4V2MsSy122nITgRvk0PHAtM86r4l1UozjoRM_JbPgDjztt3Th-VruqyF6HiQNKnafxxJljVIwEVNpMqJLPw6ehS9nCu7SZ5Yzhf5A-m_C7bgtxriIuJt-FIWFq_tskx-i3KzBymes_OT35YT7-8AyRWRi0pdmMmsZ3oO0NIFSIOSjL5SF8AOUJ_ZAMe5rnUqXtKS4pNd0UkZBJ3KjyXxm-EGPt8hi2e4VJSGZWPexJShjdRgf3cQ4cPkZ_SxzbzXq-fNBPIIUeZ31e8JyxvFhPkKVD76STY0lo0w/4rIAOJxUSTJVJEjWYjhzSx8kTakWA70v/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"A Mantra for 2026: ‘Adapt and Survive’\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">Maybe the metaverse is still coming</a>.)  </p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">The difference between these two possible futures is government, says Alan Iny, one of the report’s authors and a partner at BCG. “Imagine a world where the governments have less power and the corporations have more,” he says of the digital Darwinism scenario. “If corporations do come up with some cool cancer treatment there is no reason to assume, at least to me, that it will flow through to the masses.” In other words, <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/CR6wYicrwcZw2R9KxWYfs8Nhc0RWJV5xVpDsWIZiuGLR0dKOgwudVzLTBFxSonWGrRohBEzIw8zNTLy6WCDtpkZCFrnFbBdQDaUlKMYX3XR2Nt0btLuAbRiJLkRWeJBbQjPdrLxZQUjpoVrBZebaIPtJHTzl9nDl6nnfirk4qxo8-IRAZqW7nrh-L5azzPhpdM5Ce0J5xvpWUXb8Vlw6mjwQGhb7LvwhGJRpDBMbNpPQxQuPffgjD2ijs60wOTkMHaundoXbRBTXcscw8ZFhXhde1NfMaivkfw1Ox9R84SR_Cw0CvjR6Kh6dWny6UOSHdfZwuufHShqsQfirLmjEnIgEK2VKSqo_EpMgPbYreG9H62Okz8c0Pbp0lrwJRSB8gw8a7ZLZfo5-fBcJEwjV_WDxw8-bqyHLyRjTEnXh_N0o2gX-v9WCmiINGed1QT-xZJ5OS0AgULufToryYFddLLym0eSr22OwiorRN0kp1UYLUUw5gxqMBBMoMtkena8D650-BNlEguXHrgLdPvGwa-MCtHQ/dDy58-neyOI4lIB0fAUxGRCAj4N_pRne/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"2024 Was the Year of Bots, Bullets and Bitcoin\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">when technical progress outpaces politics, bad stuff tends to happen</a>.</p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">The path to the abundance scenario isn’t seamless either. The report imagines massive cyberattacks in the 2030s that lead to an AI treaty; it takes a disaster to put the world on a better path. “If I just put the AI abundance scenario out there people would just say you’re crazy, you’re being naive, that’s never going to happen,” says Iny.</p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><em style=\"font-size:16px\">— Walter Frick, Bloomberg Weekend</em></p><h2 style=\"font-size:24px;line-height:30px;font-weight:700;padding-top:12px;border-top:1px solid;margin-top:40px\">What Are the Chances...</h2><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><strong style=\"font-size:16px\">Will Robots Ever Be Able to Make Coffee?</strong></p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">In 2007, Apple co-founder Steve Wozniak predicted that robots would “never” be able to make a cup of coffee — meaning walk up to and operate an unfamiliar coffee machine. But AI experts now predict that a robot will pass the “coffee test” somewhere in the 2030s, with a median prediction of 2034. <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/s/c/18wA4D7L0uwdGaxex5wBMDxlovzU6NVUCKCkFDzFG54hPp20VjKm07gdDDtMqrPU0oT-jNkBbtm27vrJzE83J_jhs6VMSns1P55Ex2Q2zFHhCjrlBp1Hey8hlSq-rb1Gszvl0FYD0v86KH6AWXbBt8ibQZpDLXGL7n5jh2Uh7cUGapvJUr1OATvDZwHGhM_17I-YX4TeHFaYOr5ZVf02BoxcFB-heTRUbPjQzgdPyRD_JD9cl0tsJrtB6-s9ptpVpylQnUd1B9JGvap2c1tJ1aa8_abTOZRYrygAQC0w52vtVcQx4ktFsWSoNoCaY5cRU5kcxBcP98TvSP-9TK9gIZhZyIu_pUk8/nduSuuPbwHzncM3FhOE_yu1DuX2smoAV/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"When Will Robots Pass the &quot;Coffee Test&quot;? Expert Forecasts on the Future of Robotics\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">That’s from the LEAP forecasting competition</a> run by the Forecasting Research Institute, which we’ve <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/a/sc/xUu3-zmVWWYyV9vVMzJ8-i9e97wwZYhjSF0Ug5t59ftHmBxr5ujkygyF2cw6rxaAY-lMxl4H2YvJZ1MoWkr__xZ8MqRuCzEW2bImP6E8bYmt-KH7dCuiVoRN_BdA1DhgnNPb2vTKObGb0V2NFwQQKG7wJyGq1wY0PjXshx31xER6tDyz3JLD7Q6UK_D0aLBIP0gx50EV8bxi6OAjrReKh2x3SWlRVqSahKIpW0SElXkwc3y9XLIGswayVvvtTjNc71Cm65WLQcc3vIE1V0FHnw8nj6bq7DuHo0Z12FKljqpteyeRcVJzhe2qXVaXkV4mLzKr6UJ-TKbH01qyNEJL69TUFX0vmnx-adZ9Dj68YRqlB5MHytFLBQZwu5zWtSKUa4ay89EaOmoKGylpd9fNkhUW61EmuvNcQXzAGv3mzzpo6wNX_VsiRG4RVtCEpHGk_yufOTxNjqPlZDyh0CQyyOzshVHwJ33pIGD6kzZ6cwgw3c9M_gWP3gQjU17Aj6dzpz5eAjFDj3QcIY6qzVjlmQ/6XcOAmLFD3dPkQmtXcs5FnWEO3nEnGCf/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"AI Needs Fewer Prophets and More Predictions\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"font-size:inherit;color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid\">written about before</a>. The “coffee test” here “requires a robot to make a cup of coffee in three different unstructured, unfamiliar environments of equivalent complexity to an ordinary home, without making any mistakes.” </p><figure style=\"margin:20px 0;max-width:580px\"><!--[if mso]><table width=\"580\"><tr><td><img src=\"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/ipZGBKCyL9vU/v3/pidjEfPlU1QWZop3vfGKsrX.ke8XuWirGYh1PKgEw44kE/-1x-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"580\"/></td></tr></table><div style=\"display:none\"><![endif]--> <img src=\"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/ipZGBKCyL9vU/v3/pidjEfPlU1QWZop3vfGKsrX.ke8XuWirGYh1PKgEw44kE/-1x-1.png\" alt style=\"width:100%;display:block;margin-bottom:4px;max-width:580px\"><!--[if mso]></div><![endif]--></figure><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">In addition to forecasts from AI experts, the LEAP project includes predictions from so-called “superforecasters” who’ve distinguished themselves with accurate predictions in previous tournaments on unrelated topics. And their forecasts are slightly more bullish: The median superforecaster predicts a robot will pass the coffee test in 2032. </p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">I guess put your coffee machine on notice? Starting next decade it’ll be robot pour-overs only.</p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><em style=\"font-size:16px\">— Walter Frick, Bloomberg Weekend </em></p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\">(Disclosure: I was previously a contributing editor at FRI.)</p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><strong style=\"font-size:16px\">Tell us what you think:</strong></p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><strong style=\"font-size:16px\">When will a robot pass the “coffee test” — defined as the ability to prepare a cup of coffee in an unfamiliar home?</strong></p><p style=\"margin-top:24px;font-size:16px\"><em style=\"font-size:16px\">The median AI expert in the LEAP forecasting project predicts a robot will pass the test by 2034. Too soon? Or too late?</em></p><ul style=\"margin-top:24px;padding-inline-start:24px\"><li style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:400;line-height:1.4;font-size:16px\"><a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/s/c/vZBKRr-gYrOA8ySepPgpAMvJoSHLIVN85NPrw1BTohW0L5nhnOOwQmA3SEd105YGRsZgmx-O6T1MHVeihbebElq-d1r29Zh_5tK2bLJHinPl37-Gf2_eWB_XjThA1Qzp-GeRGTSLY4uV-rGICb6WQ0F6t96r2ejMJZgQaTwN_k_lA8n7QSAOYRVwSuDXC9mrCRlWd9FAmUDbzrM4KCzmq7uplsdVopezZDbO291F_7dmbPqJX1loqkOvnHcCDwEdrtofdnPYY9Bb7nHLg5HY-WWBL52AVakOj2GJyl5Mu9A7XH4zhBf8YHf44VK2JqjNaVAoOhqbZQ/oP0MNyqua5jyexg75V8BN9Y80XSdk35Y/20\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" title=\"Qualtrics Survey | Qualtrics Experience Management\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color:#00e;text-decoration-line:underline;text-decoration-style:solid;font-size:16px\">Before or during 2034</a></li><li style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:400;line-height:1.4;font-size:16px\"><a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/s/c/F02-NRNqBUZHO7PaKj7wJAtLB9iYavvoIIPXSp_klgWbWLcfQ4gqTC6Atkg77Ru-R6DS2bjjcOS3l5bG4H0i3MN84DfsG5t9gAibJm7YCI5oVpZ_qOmU0E0Bp5VarENaCi_HhJSx93e8FGt2fYCDn3